WEBVTT

00:20.280 --> 00:20.760
35.

00:22.940 --> 00:26.820
He did not leave for Cambridge the next day, as he had said he would.

00:27.660 --> 00:41.100
He deferred his departure a whole week, and during that time he made me feel what severe punishment a good yet stern and conscientious, yet implacable man can inflict on one who has offended him.

00:41.740 --> 00:52.040
Without one overt act of hostility, one abrading word, he contrived to impress me momently with the conviction that I was put beyond the pale of his favor.

00:53.060 --> 01:02.080
Not that St. John harbored a spirit of unchristian vindictiveness, not that he would have injured a hair of my head if it had been fully in his power to do so.

01:02.780 --> 01:07.660
Both by nature and principle, he was superior to the mean gratification of vengeance.

01:08.400 --> 01:18.740
He had forgiven me for saying I scorned him and his love, but he had not forgotten the words, and as long as he and I lived, he never would forget them.

01:18.740 --> 01:31.900
I saw by his look when he turned to me that they were always written on the air between him and me, whenever I spoke they sounded in my voice to his ear, and their echo toned every answer he gave me.

01:31.900 --> 02:00.460
He did not abstain from conversing with me. He even called me as usual each morning to join him at his desk, and I fear the corrupt man within him had a pleasure unimparted to and unshared by the pure Christian, in evincing with what skill he could, while acting and speaking apparently just as usual, extract from every deed and every phrase the spirit of interest and approval which had formerly communicated a certain austere charm to his language and manner.

02:00.460 --> 02:11.900
To me he was in reality become no longer flesh but marble. His eye was a cold bright blue gem, his tongue a speaking instrument, nothing more.

02:13.080 --> 02:24.160
All this was torture to me, refined lingering torture. It kept up a slow fire of indignation and a trembling trouble of grief which harassed and crushed me altogether.

02:24.880 --> 02:40.240
I felt how, if I were his wife, this good man, pure as the deep sunless source, could soon kill me, without drawing from my veins a single drop of blood or receiving on his own crystal conscience the faintest stain of crime.

02:41.140 --> 03:04.420
Especially I felt this when I made any attempt to propitiate him. No Ruth met my Ruth. He experienced no suffering from estrangement, no yearning after reconciliation, and though more than once my fast falling tears blistered the page over which we both bent, they produced no more effect on him than if his heart had been really a matter of stone or metal.

03:05.300 --> 03:22.260
To his sisters meantime he was somewhat kinder than usual, as if afraid that mere coldness would not sufficiently convince me how completely I was banished and banned. He added the force of contrast. And this I am sure he did not by malice but on principle.

03:23.160 --> 03:47.440
The night before he left home, happening to see him walking in the garden about sunset, and remembering, as I looked at him, that this man, alienated as he now was, had once saved my life and that we were near relations, I was moved to make a last attempt to regain his friendship. I went out and approached him as he stood leaning over the little gate. I spoke to the point at once.

03:48.460 --> 03:53.500
St. John, I am unhappy because you are still angry with me. Let us be friends.

03:54.720 --> 04:06.600
I hope we are friends, was the unmoved reply while he still watched the rising of the moon, which he had been contemplating as I approached. No, St. John, we are not friends as we were. You know that.

04:07.480 --> 04:12.580
Are we not? That is wrong. For my part I wish you no ill and all good.

04:13.380 --> 04:27.900
I believe you, St. John, for I am sure you are incapable of wishing any one ill. But, as I am your kinswoman, I should desire somewhat more of affection than that sort of general philanthropy you extend to mere strangers.

04:28.600 --> 04:35.400
Of course, he said, your wish is reasonable, and I am far from regarding you as a stranger.

04:36.200 --> 04:51.560
This, spoken in a cool, tranquil tone, was mortifying and baffling enough. Had I attended to the suggestions of pride and ire, I should immediately have left him. But something worked within me more strongly than those feelings could.

04:51.560 --> 05:03.720
I deeply venerated my cousin's talent and principle. His friendship was of value to me. To lose it tried me severely. I would not so soon relinquish the attempt to reconquer it.

05:05.180 --> 05:12.400
Must we part in this way, St. John? And when you go to India, will you leave me so, without a kinder word than you have yet spoken?

05:13.180 --> 05:16.340
He now turned quite from the moon and faced me.

05:17.020 --> 05:22.000
When I go to India, Jane, will I leave you? What, do you not go to India?

05:23.120 --> 05:25.580
You said I could not unless I married you.

05:26.740 --> 05:29.600
And you will not marry me? You adhere to that resolution?

05:31.380 --> 05:44.940
Reader, do you know, as I do, what terror those cold people can put into the ice of their questions? How much of the fall of the avalanche is in their anger? Of the breaking up of the frozen sea and their displeasure?

05:46.000 --> 05:50.020
No, St. John, I will not marry you. I adhere to my resolution.

05:51.180 --> 05:55.900
The avalanche had shaken and slid a little forward, but it did not yet crash down.

05:56.840 --> 06:00.940
Once more, why this refusal? He asked.

06:02.040 --> 06:11.840
Formerly, I answered, because you did not love me. Now, I replied, because you almost hate me. If I were to marry you, you would kill me. You are killing me now.

06:13.520 --> 06:16.420
His lips and cheeks turned white, quite white.

06:17.200 --> 06:20.200
I should kill you? I am killing you?

06:20.200 --> 06:39.000
Your words are such as ought not to be used, violent, unfeminine, and untrue. They betray an unfortunate state of mind. They merit severe reproof. They would seem inexcusable, but that it is the duty of man to forgive his fellow, even until seventy and seven times.

06:39.840 --> 06:52.240
I had finished the business now. While earnestly wishing to erase from his mind the trace of my former offence, I had stamped on that tenacious surface another and far deeper impression. I had burnt it in.

06:53.400 --> 07:01.240
Now you will indeed hate me, I said. It is useless to attempt to conciliate you. I see I have made an eternal enemy of you.

07:02.160 --> 07:14.580
A fresh wrong did these words inflict, the worst because they touched on the truth. That bloodless lip quivered to a temporary spasm. I knew the steely ire I had whetted. I was heart-rung.

07:15.600 --> 07:23.400
You utterly misinterpret my words, I said at once, seizing his hand. I have no intention to grieve or pain you. Indeed, I have not.

07:24.480 --> 07:29.500
Most bitterly he smiled. Most decidedly, he withdrew his hand from mine.

07:30.420 --> 07:38.140
And now you recall your promise, and will not go to India at all, I presume, said he after a considerable pause.

07:38.760 --> 07:41.960
Yes, I will, as your assistant, I answered.

07:42.900 --> 07:50.400
A very long silence succeeded. What struggle there was in him between nature and grace in this interval I cannot tell.

07:50.980 --> 07:59.080
Only singular gleams scintillated in his eyes, and strange shadows passed over his face. He spoke at last.

08:00.240 --> 08:09.420
I before proved to you the absurdity of a single woman of your age proposing to accompany abroad a single man of mine.

08:10.120 --> 08:19.820
I proved it to you in such terms as I should have thought would have prevented your ever again alluding to the plan. That you have done so I regret for your sake.

08:20.560 --> 08:25.920
I interrupted him. Anything like a tangible reproach gave me courage at once.

08:26.720 --> 08:32.580
Keep to common sense, St. John, you are verging on nonsense. You pretend to be shocked by what I have said.

08:32.860 --> 08:40.740
You are not really shocked, for with your superior mind you cannot be either so dull or so conceited as to misunderstand my meaning.

08:41.420 --> 08:46.200
I say again, I will be your curate, if you like, but never your wife.

08:47.120 --> 08:55.280
Again he turned lividly pale, but as before controlled his passion perfectly. He answered emphatically but calmly.

08:56.560 --> 09:03.600
A female curate who is not my wife would never suit me. With me then it seems you cannot go.

09:04.000 --> 09:11.440
But if you are sincere in your offer, I will while in town speak to a married missionary whose wife needs a coadjutor.

09:11.440 --> 09:22.660
Your own fortune will make you independent of the society's aid, and thus you may still be spared the dishonor of breaking your promise and deserting the band you engage to join.

09:23.400 --> 09:36.500
Now, I never had, as the reader knows, either given any formal promise or entered into any engagement, and this language was all much too hard and much too despotic for the occasion.

09:36.500 --> 09:49.040
I replied, There is no dishonor, no breach of promise, no desertion in the case. I am not under the slightest obligation to go to India, especially with strangers.

09:49.740 --> 09:56.520
With you I would have ventured much, because I admire, confide in, and as a sister I love you.

09:56.860 --> 10:02.680
But I am convinced that, go when and with whom I would, I should not live long in that climate.

10:03.920 --> 10:07.880
Ah, you are afraid of yourself, he said, curling his lip.

10:08.960 --> 10:17.920
I am. God did not give me my life to throw away, and to do, as you would wish me, would, I begin to think, be almost equivalent to committing suicide.

10:19.260 --> 10:27.880
Moreover, before I definitely resolve on quitting England, I will know for certain whether I cannot be of greater use by remaining in it than by leaving it.

10:28.280 --> 10:29.600
What do you mean?

10:30.500 --> 10:40.500
It would be fruitless to attempt to explain, but there is a point on which I have long endured painful doubt, and I can go nowhere till by some means that doubt is removed.

10:41.700 --> 10:55.500
I know where your heart turns, and to what it clings. The interest you cherish is lawless and unconsecrated. Long since you ought to have crushed it. Now you should blush to allude to it. You think of Mr. Rochester?

10:56.240 --> 10:59.540
It was true. I confessed it by silence.

11:00.440 --> 11:02.920
Are you going to seek Mr. Rochester?

11:03.720 --> 11:06.360
I must find out what has become of him.

11:07.560 --> 11:18.620
It remains for me then, he said, to remember you in my prayers, and to entreat God for you, in all earnestness, that you may not indeed become a castaway.

11:18.620 --> 11:26.860
I had thought I recognized in you one of the Chosen, but God sees not as man sees. His will be done.

11:28.340 --> 11:34.260
He opened the gate, passed through it, and strayed away down the Glen. He was soon out of sight.

11:35.520 --> 11:39.900
On re-entering the parlour, I found Diana standing at the window, looking very thoughtful.

11:41.260 --> 11:47.180
Diana was a great deal taller than I. She put her hand on my shoulder, and stooping, examined my face.

11:48.160 --> 11:54.680
Jane, she said, you are always agitated and pale now. I am sure there is something the matter.

11:55.560 --> 11:58.280
Tell me what business St. John and you have on hand.

11:59.020 --> 12:10.240
I have watched you this half hour from the window. You must forgive my being such a spy, but for a long time I have fancied I hardly know what. St. John is a strange being.

12:11.240 --> 12:16.120
She paused. I did not speak. Soon she resumed.

12:17.340 --> 12:27.840
That brother of mine cherishes peculiar views of some sort respecting you, I am sure. He has long distinguished you by a notice and interest he never showed to any one else.

12:28.420 --> 12:32.060
To what end? I wish he loved you, does he, Jane?

12:33.380 --> 12:38.140
I put her cool hand to my hot forehead. No die, not one wit.

12:39.500 --> 12:46.420
Then why does he follow you so with his eyes, and get you so frequently alone with him, and keep you so continually at his side?

12:47.180 --> 12:50.380
Mary and I had both concluded he wished you to marry him.

12:51.360 --> 12:54.780
He does. He has asked me to be his wife.

12:55.480 --> 13:03.540
Diana clapped her hands. That is just what we hoped and thought. And you will marry him, Jane, won't you? And then he will stay in England.

13:04.900 --> 13:12.320
Far from that, Diana. His sole idea in proposing to me is to procure a fitting fellow-labourer in his Indian toils.

13:13.500 --> 13:16.120
What? He wishes you to go to India?

13:17.420 --> 13:17.980
Yes.

13:19.180 --> 13:27.160
Madness, she exclaimed. You would not live three months there, I am certain. You shall never go. You have not consented, have you, Jane?

13:28.040 --> 13:30.020
I have refused to marry him.

13:31.180 --> 13:34.660
And have consequently displeased him, she suggested.

13:36.080 --> 13:41.660
Deeply. He will never forgive me, I fear. Yet I offered to accompany him as his sister.

13:42.680 --> 13:52.520
It was frantic folly to do so, Jane. Think of the task you undertook, one of incessant fatigue, where fatigue kills even the strong. And you are weak.

13:53.160 --> 14:05.000
St. John, you know him, would urge you to impossibilities. With him there would be no permission to rest during the hot hours, and unfortunately I have noticed, whatever he exacts, you force yourself to perform.

14:05.560 --> 14:08.640
I am astonished you found courage to refuse his hand.

14:09.280 --> 14:11.180
You do not love him, then, Jane?

14:11.860 --> 14:13.200
Not as a husband.

14:14.300 --> 14:15.720
Yet he is a handsome fellow.

14:16.840 --> 14:20.200
And I am so plain, you see, Di. We should never suit.

14:21.820 --> 14:28.940
Plain? You? Not at all. You are much too pretty, as well as too good, to be grilled alive in Calcutta.

14:29.660 --> 14:33.920
And again she earnestly conjured me to give up all thoughts of going out with her brother.

14:34.820 --> 14:44.140
I must indeed, I said, for when just now I repeated the offer of serving him for a deacon, he expressed himself shocked at my want of decency.

14:44.800 --> 14:56.720
He seemed to think I had committed an impropriety in proposing to accompany him unmarried, as if I had not from the first hoped to find in him a brother, and habitually regarded him as such.

14:57.700 --> 15:00.260
What makes you say he does not love you, Jane?

15:01.100 --> 15:09.140
You should hear himself on the subject. He has again and again explained that it is not himself, but his office he wishes to mate.

15:09.940 --> 15:15.120
He has told me I am formed for labor, not for love, which is true, no doubt.

15:15.660 --> 15:20.840
But, in my opinion, if I am not formed for love, it follows that I am not formed for marriage.

15:21.960 --> 15:27.540
Would it not be strange, Di, to be chained for life to a man who regarded one but as a useful tool?

15:29.160 --> 15:32.320
Insupportable, unnatural, out of the question.

15:33.760 --> 15:47.640
And then, I continued, though I have only sisterly affection for him now, yet, if forced to be his wife, I can imagine the possibility of conceiving an inevitable strange, torturing kind of love for him,

15:47.640 --> 15:53.840
because he is so talented, and there is often a certain heroic grandeur in his look, manner, and conversation.

15:55.000 --> 15:58.260
In that case, my lot would become unspeakably wretched.

15:58.960 --> 16:07.400
He would not want me to love him, and if I showed the feeling, he would make me sensible that it was a superfluity unrequired by him, unbecoming in me.

16:07.780 --> 16:08.800
I know he would.

16:09.540 --> 16:13.160
And yet St. John is a good man, said Diana.

16:13.860 --> 16:23.860
He is a good and a great man, but he forgets pitilessly the feelings and claims of little people in pursuing his own large views.

16:24.680 --> 16:31.620
It is better, therefore, for the insignificant to keep out of his way, lest in his progress he should trample them down.

16:32.460 --> 16:35.120
Here he comes. I will leave you, Diana.

16:35.440 --> 16:38.380
And I hastened upstairs as I saw him entering the garden.

16:39.140 --> 16:41.380
But I was forced to meet him again at supper.

16:41.940 --> 16:45.060
During that meal he appeared just as composed as usual.

16:45.760 --> 16:51.820
I had thought he would hardly speak to me, and I was certain he had given up the pursuit of his matrimonial scheme.

16:52.780 --> 16:55.500
The sequel showed I was mistaken on both points.

16:56.240 --> 17:03.640
He addressed me precisely in his ordinary manner, or what had, of late, been his ordinary manner, one scrupulously polite.

17:04.240 --> 17:13.460
No doubt he had invoked the help of the Holy Spirit to subdue the anger I had roused in him, and now believed he had forgiven me once more.

17:14.160 --> 17:18.940
For the evening reading before prayers, he selected the twenty-first chapter of Revelation.

17:19.860 --> 17:25.180
It was at all times pleasant to listen, while from his lips fell the words of the Bible.

17:26.000 --> 17:29.300
Never did his fine voice sound at once so sweet and full.

17:29.300 --> 17:36.400
Never did his manner become so impressive in its noble simplicity as when he delivered the Oracles of God.

17:37.120 --> 17:44.560
And to-night that voice took a more solemn tone, that manner a more thrilling meaning, as he sat in the midst of his household circle,

17:45.420 --> 17:52.180
the May moon shining in through the uncurtain window, and rendering almost unnecessary the light of the candle on the table.

17:52.920 --> 18:01.200
As he sat there, bending over the great old Bible, and described from its page the vision of the new heaven and the new earth,

18:01.980 --> 18:10.700
told how God would come to dwell with men, how He would wipe away all tears from their eyes, and promised that there should be no more death,

18:11.300 --> 18:17.060
neither sorrow, nor crying, nor any more pain, because the former things were passed away.

18:17.840 --> 18:26.660
The succeeding words thrilled me strangely as he spoke them, especially as I felt by the slight indescribable alteration in sound,

18:27.680 --> 18:30.340
that in uttering them his eye had turned on me.

18:30.340 --> 18:41.740
He that overcometh shall inherit all things, and I will be his God, and he shall be my son, but, was slowly distinctly read,

18:42.540 --> 18:52.800
the fearful, the unbelieving, etc., shall have their part in the lake which burneth with fire and brimstone, which is the second death.

18:54.440 --> 18:57.400
Henceforward I knew what fate St. John feared for me.

18:58.560 --> 19:06.680
A calm, subdued triumph, blent with a longing earnestness, marked his enunciation of the last glorious verses of that chapter.

19:07.500 --> 19:15.440
The reader believed his name was already written in the Lamb's Book of Life, and he yearned after the hour which should admit him to the city

19:15.440 --> 19:21.960
to which the kings of the earth bring their glory and honor, which has no need of sun or moon to shine in it,

19:22.120 --> 19:26.360
because the glory of God lightens it, and the Lamb is the light thereof.

19:27.200 --> 19:32.700
In the prayer following the chapter, all his energy gathered, all his stern zeal awoke.

19:33.100 --> 19:37.860
He was in deep earnest, wrestling with God and resolved on a conquest.

19:37.860 --> 19:42.780
He supplicated strength for the weak-hearted, guidance for wanderers from the fold,

19:42.860 --> 19:50.920
a return, even at the eleventh hour, for those whom the temptations of the world and the flesh were luring from the narrow path.

19:51.540 --> 19:56.020
He asked, he urged, he claimed the boon of a brand snatched from the burning.

19:57.100 --> 19:59.120
Earnestness is ever deeply solemn.

20:00.040 --> 20:03.140
First, as I listened to that prayer, I wondered at his.

20:03.920 --> 20:09.000
Then, when it continued in rows, I was touched by it, and at last awed.

20:09.620 --> 20:13.320
He felt the greatness and goodness of his purpose so sincerely.

20:14.140 --> 20:17.500
Others who heard him plead for it could not but feel it too.

20:18.500 --> 20:20.740
The prayer over, we took leave of him.

20:21.120 --> 20:23.780
He was to go at a very early hour in the morning.

20:24.700 --> 20:30.660
Diana and Mary, having kissed him, left the room, in compliance, I think, with a whispered hint from him.

20:30.660 --> 20:34.240
I tendered my hand and wished him a pleasant journey.

20:35.540 --> 20:40.140
Thank you, Jane. As I said, I shall return from Cambridge in a fortnight.

20:40.740 --> 20:42.860
That space, then, is left you for reflection.

20:44.000 --> 20:48.580
If I listen to human pride, I should say no more to you of marriage with me.

20:48.900 --> 20:55.540
But I listen to my duty, and keep steadily in view my first aim, to do all things to the glory of God.

20:56.440 --> 20:59.820
My master was long-suffering, so will I be.

20:59.820 --> 21:03.440
I cannot give you up to perdition as a vessel of wrath.

21:04.480 --> 21:07.060
Repent, resolve while there is yet time.

21:07.800 --> 21:10.440
Remember, we are bid to work while it is day.

21:11.140 --> 21:14.040
Warned that the night cometh when no man shall work.

21:14.940 --> 21:18.940
Remember the fate of Dives, who had his good things in this life.

21:19.520 --> 21:23.920
God give you strength to choose that better part which shall not be taken from you.

21:24.660 --> 21:27.860
He laid his hand on my head as he uttered the last words.

21:27.860 --> 21:30.720
He had spoken earnestly, mildly.

21:31.160 --> 21:34.580
His look was not, indeed, that of a lover beholding his mistress.

21:35.240 --> 21:39.040
But it was that of a pastor recalling his wandering sheep,

21:39.420 --> 21:43.040
or better, of a guardian angel watching the soul for which he is responsible.

21:44.500 --> 21:47.740
All men of talent, whether they be men of feeling or not,

21:48.160 --> 21:51.240
whether they be zealots, or aspirants, or despots,

21:51.820 --> 21:55.580
provided only they be sincere, have their sublime moments,

21:55.580 --> 21:57.780
when they subdue and rule.

21:58.580 --> 22:02.860
I felt veneration for St. John, veneration so strong

22:02.860 --> 22:06.600
that its impetus thrust me at once to the point I had so long shunned.

22:07.580 --> 22:09.860
I was tempted to see struggling with him,

22:10.340 --> 22:14.040
to rush down the torrent of his will into the gulf of his existence,

22:14.700 --> 22:16.440
and there lose my own.

22:17.440 --> 22:20.320
I was almost as hard beset by him now

22:20.320 --> 22:23.640
as I had been once before in a different way by another.

22:24.300 --> 22:26.760
I was a fool both times.

22:27.440 --> 22:30.080
To have yielded then would have been an error of principle.

22:30.820 --> 22:33.740
To have yielded now would have been an error of judgment.

22:34.780 --> 22:37.700
So I think at this hour, when I look back to the crisis

22:37.700 --> 22:39.480
through the quiet medium of time,

22:40.200 --> 22:42.600
I was unconscious of folly at the instant.

22:43.900 --> 22:46.540
I stood motionless under my hierophant's touch.

22:47.140 --> 22:50.040
My refusals were forgotten, my fears overcome,

22:50.680 --> 22:52.280
my wrestlings paralyzed.

22:53.640 --> 22:56.280
Everything that was possible, i.e. my marriage with St. John,

22:56.640 --> 22:58.380
was fast becoming the possible.

22:59.380 --> 23:01.880
All was changing utterly with a sudden sweep.

23:02.600 --> 23:05.640
Religion called, angels beckoned, God commanded,

23:05.820 --> 23:07.920
life rolled together like a scroll,

23:08.760 --> 23:11.540
death's gates opening, showed eternity beyond.

23:12.440 --> 23:14.980
It seemed that for safety and bliss there,

23:15.560 --> 23:17.800
all here might be sacrificed in a second.

23:18.500 --> 23:20.740
The dim room was full of visions.

23:20.740 --> 23:24.280
Could you decide now? asked the missionary.

23:25.080 --> 23:27.420
The inquiry was put in gentle tones.

23:27.780 --> 23:29.540
He drew me to him gently.

23:30.320 --> 23:34.180
Oh, that gentleness, how far more potent is it than force.

23:35.060 --> 23:37.040
I could resist St. John's wrath.

23:37.860 --> 23:40.340
I grew pliant as a reed under his kindness.

23:41.380 --> 23:43.880
Yet I knew all the time, if I yielded now,

23:44.380 --> 23:48.260
I should not the less be made to repent some day of my former rebellion.

23:49.220 --> 23:50.720
His nature was not changed,

23:50.740 --> 23:52.300
by one hour of solemn prayer.

23:52.860 --> 23:54.180
It was only elevated.

23:55.600 --> 23:58.720
I could decide if I were but certain, I answered,

23:59.260 --> 24:03.060
were I but convinced that it is God's will I should marry you.

24:03.320 --> 24:06.520
I could vow to marry you here and now, come afterwards what would.

24:07.720 --> 24:10.860
My prayers are heard, ejaculated St. John.

24:11.300 --> 24:14.800
He pressed his hand firmer on my head, as if he claimed me.

24:15.080 --> 24:19.720
He surrounded me with his arm, almost as if he loved me.

24:19.720 --> 24:22.560
I say almost, I knew the difference,

24:23.100 --> 24:25.480
for I had felt what it was to be loved.

24:26.300 --> 24:29.420
But, like him, I had now put love out of the question,

24:29.560 --> 24:30.680
and thought only of duty.

24:31.860 --> 24:34.440
I contended with my inward dimness of vision,

24:35.100 --> 24:36.920
before which clouds yet rolled.

24:37.800 --> 24:43.820
I sincerely, deeply, fervently longed to do what was right, and only that.

24:45.180 --> 24:48.340
Show me, show me the path, I entreated of heaven.

24:48.340 --> 24:51.260
I was excited more than I had ever been,

24:51.720 --> 24:55.520
and whether what followed was the effect of excitement the reader shall judge.

24:56.520 --> 24:58.080
All the house was still,

24:58.800 --> 25:02.960
for I believe all, except St. John and myself, were now retired to rest.

25:03.800 --> 25:05.600
The one candle was dying out.

25:06.480 --> 25:08.400
The room was full of moonlight.

25:09.260 --> 25:11.080
My heart beat fast and thick.

25:11.660 --> 25:12.900
I heard its throb.

25:13.880 --> 25:17.940
Suddenly it stood still to an inexpressible feeling that thrilled it through,

25:18.340 --> 25:20.600
and passed at once to my head and extremities.

25:21.880 --> 25:24.180
The feeling was not like an electric shock,

25:24.860 --> 25:27.980
but it was quite as sharp, as strange, as startling.

25:28.640 --> 25:32.280
It acted on my senses, as if their utmost activity,

25:32.580 --> 25:34.420
hitherto had been but torpor,

25:35.320 --> 25:38.080
from which they were now summoned and forced to wake.

25:38.720 --> 25:40.200
They rose expectant.

25:40.540 --> 25:43.740
Eye and ear waited, while the flesh quivered on my bones.

25:45.360 --> 25:47.700
What have you heard, what do you see?

25:48.120 --> 25:48.860
asked St. John.

25:49.640 --> 25:52.980
I saw nothing, but I heard a voice somewhere cry.

25:55.660 --> 25:57.980
Jane, Jane, Jane.

25:58.780 --> 25:59.680
Nothing more.

26:01.060 --> 26:03.240
Oh God, what is it? I gasped.

26:04.100 --> 26:05.920
I might have said, where is it?

26:06.060 --> 26:07.960
For it did not seem in the room,

26:08.620 --> 26:11.020
nor in the house, nor in the garden.

26:11.020 --> 26:15.320
It did not come out of the air, nor from under the earth, nor from overhead.

26:16.220 --> 26:20.620
I had heard it, where or whence, forever impossible to know.

26:21.680 --> 26:23.740
And it was the voice of a human being,

26:24.040 --> 26:26.340
a known, loved, well-remembered voice,

26:26.840 --> 26:29.500
that of Edward Fairfax, Rochester.

26:30.240 --> 26:34.020
And it spoke in pain and woe wildly, eerily, urgently.

26:35.020 --> 26:38.880
I am coming, I cried. Wait for me. Oh, I will come.

26:38.880 --> 26:41.720
I flew to the door and looked into the passage.

26:41.800 --> 26:44.220
It was dark. I ran out into the garden.

26:44.580 --> 26:45.420
It was void.

26:46.200 --> 26:48.260
Where are you? I exclaimed.

26:49.120 --> 26:52.380
The hills beyond Marsh Glen sent the answer faintly back.

26:53.220 --> 26:54.320
Where are you?

26:55.020 --> 26:55.820
I listened.

26:56.780 --> 26:58.940
The wind sighed low in the firs.

26:59.360 --> 27:01.960
All was moorland loneliness and midnight hush.

27:03.340 --> 27:07.380
Down superstition I commented as that spectre rose up black,

27:07.380 --> 27:09.920
by the black yew at the gate.

27:10.580 --> 27:13.620
This is not thy deception, not thy witchcraft.

27:14.040 --> 27:15.360
It is the work of nature.

27:15.880 --> 27:19.800
She was aroused and did no miracle but her best.

27:20.740 --> 27:24.660
I broke from St. John, who had followed, and would have detained me.

27:25.180 --> 27:27.560
It was my time to assume ascendancy.

27:28.060 --> 27:30.240
My powers were in play and in force.

27:30.700 --> 27:33.220
I told him to forbear question or remark.

27:33.540 --> 27:35.240
I desired him to leave me.

27:35.240 --> 27:37.400
I must and would be alone.

27:38.060 --> 27:39.360
He obeyed at once.

27:39.980 --> 27:44.020
Where there is energy to command well enough, obedience never fails.

27:44.560 --> 27:50.960
I mounted to my chamber, locked myself in, fell on my knees, and prayed in my way.

27:51.220 --> 27:55.080
A different way to St. John's, but effective in its own fashion.

27:55.760 --> 28:01.940
I seemed to penetrate very near a mighty spirit, and my soul rushed out in gratitude at his feet.

28:01.940 --> 28:10.620
I rose from the thanksgiving, took a resolve, and lay down, unscared, enlightened, eager but for the daylight.

